  "concubinageChecklistTitle1": "Write a will",
  "concubinageChecklistDesc1": "Without a will, your partner inherits nothing — everything goes to your parents or siblings. A handwritten will (written by hand, dated, signed) is sufficient. You can bequeath the disposable portion to your partner.",
  "concubinageChecklistTitle2": "LPP beneficiary clause",
  "concubinageChecklistDesc2": "Contact your pension fund to register your partner as beneficiary. Without this clause, the LPP death capital does not go to them. Most funds accept the cohabiting partner under conditions (shared household, etc.).",
  "concubinageChecklistTitle3": "Cohabitation agreement",
  "concubinageChecklistDesc3": "A written contract that regulates the sharing of expenses, property ownership, and what happens in case of separation. Not mandatory, but strongly recommended — especially if you buy property together.",
  "concubinageChecklistTitle4": "Cross life insurance",
  "concubinageChecklistDesc4": "A life insurance where each is beneficiary of the other compensates for the absence of AVS/LPP survivor pension. Compare offers — premiums depend on age and insured capital.",
  "concubinageChecklistTitle5": "Mandate in case of incapacity",
  "concubinageChecklistDesc5": "If you become unable to make decisions (accident, illness), your partner has no power of representation. A mandate in case of incapacity (CC art. 360 ff) gives them this right.",
  "concubinageChecklistTitle6": "Advance directives",
  "concubinageChecklistDesc6": "A document that specifies your medical wishes in case of incapacity. You can designate your partner as trusted person for medical decisions (CC art. 370 ff).",
  "concubinageChecklistTitle7": "Joint account for shared expenses",
  "concubinageChecklistDesc7": "A joint account simplifies the management of shared expenses (rent, groceries, bills). Clearly define each person's contribution. In case of separation, the balance is split 50/50 unless otherwise agreed.",
  "concubinageChecklistTitle8": "Joint or individual lease",
  "concubinageChecklistDesc8": "If you are on the lease with your partner, you are jointly liable. In case of separation, both must give notice. If only one is the leaseholder, the other has no right to the housing.",
  "concubinageDisclaimer": "Simplified information for educational purposes — does not constitute legal or tax advice. Rules depend on the canton, municipality and your personal situation. Consult a legal specialist for personalised advice.",
